Yeah that argument keeps being brought up as a potential reason for underperfomance. But that makes no sense to me tbh. yes, very clearly ^
advanced server trains the model while running to try to improve with the demands of the network. this is more costly, but should make the model better in the long term
template server doesn't do any training and therefore wont improve

if the network made a change, such as increasing the sequence length, then the compute per request increases.

if you VM is not equipped well enough, or your model is not as performant on these longer seq lengths, then you will perform worse
the small sequence lengths we started with made most models seem pretty good
it's not hard to predict using a small amount of data versus having more context
And you believe that is the case for all those miners?
some models are much better given more context and will outperform
it largely depends on the model they run
pretrained models generally don't have some weights set and therefore predict worse on the dataset, if they're aren't being trained on it
and if your model has been training on one smaller sequence length, it may have gotten good at that length, but given a higher sequence length, it may not perform as well
it may even perform worse because the length is larger
it may have overfit to the low sequence length
when we upgraded to the higher length the other week, I asked and was told it would be a good idea to reset the weights of my models back to the pretrained weights
if you haven't, I suggest it. this should hopefully improve performance and let your model train better on the new network params

Bittensor inflation is currently split 50/50 between serving / validating. A miner is commonly a node that does both serving and validating, but imho its best to keep these two separate.

Serving reward depends on compute power and infrastructure speed, and also model/data curation and optimization. The better your server is relative to other servers, the better it will be ranked by validators, and you'll receive reward reflecting this.

Validation reward depends mostly on the amount of stake your validator has, and whether it can continually issue workload to servers and maintain consensus on how well the servers are performing. Stake is required to secure the network by ensuring validators will lose value if they mess up consensus.

Having tao is beneficial in various ways, it increases your validator reward proportionately on average, and for servers it improves your quality of service by giving you higher priority in validator queues proportional to your hotwallet balance. Tao should also confer voting rights once the Bittensor DAO is in place.
